===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|bred}}, {{m|enm|breed}}, from {{inh|en|ang|brēad||fragment, bit, morsel, crumb", also "bread}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*braudą||cooked food, leavened bread}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰerw-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*bʰrew-||to boil, seethe}} (see {{doublet|notext=1|en|brew}}). Alternatively, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*braudaz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*brauþaz||broken piece, fragment}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰera-||to split, beat, hew, struggle}} (see {{l|en|brittle}}). Perhaps a conflation of the two. 

Cognate with {{cog|sco|breid||bread}}, {{cog|stq|Brad||bread}}, {{cog|fy|brea||bread}}, {{cog|nl|brood||bread}}, {{cog|de|Brot||bread}}, {{cog|da|-}} and {{cog|no|brød||bread}}, {{cog|sv|bröd||bread}}, {{cog|is|brauð||bread}}, {{cog|sq|brydh||I make crumbly, friable, soft}}, {{cog|la|frustum||crumb}}. 

Eclipsed non-native {{noncog|enm|payn|t=bread}}, borrowed from {{noncog|fro|pain|t=bread}}.

